Wir definieren die //Eulersche Zahl// $$e$$ als

$$
e \coloneqq \exp(1).
$$

Dann folgt

$$
e^x = \exp(x \log(\exp(1))) = \exp(x).
$$

Au√üerdem gilt:

$$
e = \lim_{n\to\infty} \left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)^n
$$

An analogy: Consider a bank that gives 100% interest per year. Now consider the bank giving 50% interest every six months and so on. If we continue doing this, the factor after one year approaches $$e$$.